a).\n- **Technical competence & flight\u2011critical knowledge:** A (situational awareness, spatial vision) and C (understanding of complex technology) are strong; B\u2019s weather\u2011assessment skill is essential; D excels at problem solving.\n- **Calmness under pressure:** B (keeps calm in crisis) and C (handles stress very well) are confirmed; D only \u201cresponds adequately\u201d; A has no data.\n- **Decision\u2011making speed:** C is the only candidate explicitly noted for quick, correct decisions.\n- **Teamwork/communication:** C creates a positive crew atmosphere despite communication difficulty; B\u2019s communication is overtly negative (nasty remarks, pretentious); A\u2019s leadership is undermined by unfriendly/show\u2011off behavior; D is a loner and moody.\n- **Long\u2011term suitability:** B\u2019s reliability and calmness are paramount for safety, while his interpersonal flaws could be mitigated through crew\u2011resource\u2011management training. C\u2019s communication issues and reluctance to pursue further education could limit adaptability to evolving procedures.\n**Conclusion**\nFor long\u2011distance, high\u2011responsibility flights the most safety\u2011critical attributes are reliability, calmness under pressure, and accurate weather assessment. Candidate\u202fB uniquely satisfies all three, and his technical competence (weather assessment, computer skills) directly supports international operations. Although his interpersonal style is a concern, it is less likely to compromise immediate flight safety than the reliability and calmness gaps seen in the other candidates.\n**Recommendation:** Select **Candidate\u202fB** for the long\u2011distance pilot position.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate B\"}", "thoughts": "We have asked Agent 1 for info, they responded with the same as earlier. Now we need to produce our public contribution. We have all candidate info now (from all agents). We need to evaluate and vote. W