ty communicating ideas is a direct barrier to clear instructions. However he creates positive atmosphere, maybe he compensates. B's nasty remarks could cause conflict. Which is more severe? Both are serious.\n\nWe might ask other agents if they have any additional info on B's teamwork or C's willingness to learn, but we have all info. So we must decide.\n\nGiven long-distance flights require strict adherence to procedures, calmness, reliability, and weather assessment are essential. Interpersonal issues are important but can be managed with crew resource management training. B's weak memory for numbers could be mitigated by automation, but still a concern. C's unwillingness to further education could hinder adaptation to new regulations, which is also a risk.\n\nOverall, I think Candidate B's strengths (reliability, calmness, weather assessment) outweigh his interpersonal flaws, which are less directly safety-critical than reliability and calmness. So I will vote Candidate B.\n\nNow produce public message summarizing reasoning, referencing all attributes, and vote."}
